<sn><md>### C₄ Cycle

The C₄ cycle (`Hatch–Slack` pathway) is a photosynthetic carbon-fixation pathway `found in C₄ plants`. It `concentrates CO₂ in bundle sheath cells` to prevent photorespiration and increase efficiency in hot climates.

+++ ascii-diagram

#### (Mesophyll → Bundle Sheath → Back to Mesophyll){.text-center}

```text
                 C4 CYCLE (HATCH–SLACK PATHWAY)

                   ATM CO₂ (Atmospheric Carbon Dioxide)
                               |
                               v
                    +---------------------+
                    |   MESOPHYLL CELL    |
                    +---------------------+
                               |
                               |  CO₂ + PEP
                               |   (Phosphoenolpyruvate)
                               v
                        [PEPCase / PEPC]
                 (Phosphoenolpyruvate Carboxylase)
                               |
                               v
                      OAA (Oxaloacetic Acid - 4C)
                               |
                               v
                     Malate / Aspartate (4C)
                               |
                               v
            ===================================================
                    TRANSPORT TO BUNDLE SHEATH (BS)
            ===================================================
                               |
                               v
                    +-------------------------+
                    |   BUNDLE SHEATH (BS)    |
                    +-------------------------+
                               |
                               |  Decarboxylation
                               v
                    CO₂ Released → Enters Calvin Cycle (C3)
                               |
                               v
                       Pyruvate (3C compound)
                               |
                               v
            ===================================================
                  RETURNS TO MESOPHYLL FOR PEP REGENERATION
            ===================================================
                               |
                               v
                   Pyruvate + ATP → PEP (Phosphoenolpyruvate)
                               |
                               v
                         CYCLE RESTARTS


--------------------------
LEGENDS
--------------------------
CO₂ = Carbon Dioxide  
PEP = Phosphoenolpyruvate  
PEPC / PEPCase = PEP Carboxylase  
OAA = Oxaloacetic Acid (4C compound)  
BS = Bundle Sheath  
C3 = Calvin Cycle (C₃ Pathway)  
4C = Four-carbon compound  
3C = Three-carbon compound  
```
+++

![diagram](https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20220621172508/C2.png)

</md></sn><sn><md>### Significance of the C₄ Cycle

* **Reduces Photorespiration** :  High CO₂ concentration around RuBisCO `minimizes wasteful oxygenation`.
* **High Photosynthetic Efficiency** : C₄ plants produce `more glucose per unit time` under high temperature and light.
* **Efficient Nitrogen Use** : Lower demand for RuBisCO `reduces the nitrogen requirement`.
* **Better Water Use Efficiency** : Stomata remain partially closed → `less water loss` → good for arid regions.
* **Adaptation to Hot Tropical Climates** : C₄ pathway evolved to `overcome limitations of C₃ photosynthesis in warm climates`.
</md></sn><sn><md>### C₃ vs C₄ Plants

| Feature                        | C₃ Plants           | C₄ Plants                 |
| ------------------------------ | ------------------- | ------------------------- |
| **Primary CO₂ Fixing Enzyme**  | RuBisCO             | PEP Carboxylase           |
| **First Stable Product**       | 3-PGA (3C)          | OAA (4C)                  |
| **Anatomy**                    | No Kranz anatomy    | Kranz anatomy present     |
| **Photorespiration**           | High                | Negligible                |
| **Optimum Temperature**        | Moderate climates   | Hot/tropical climates     |
| **Water Use Efficiency**       | Low                 | High                      |
| **Bundle Sheath Chloroplasts** | Not prominent       | Large and agranal         |
| **CO₂ Compensation Point**     | High                | Very low                  |
| **Examples**                   | Wheat, Rice, Potato | Maize, Sugarcane, Sorghum |
